---

Adds two simple lemmas about `Fin.rev`

[![Open in Gitpod](https://gitpod.io/button/open-in-gitpod.svg)](https://gitpod.io/from-referrer/)

nodes.body:
There is also `(Fin.append a b) ∘ Fin.rev = Fin.append (b ∘ Fin.rev) (a ∘ Fin.rev)`, or whatever the right statement is, I think it's this. Of which both these results are a consequence because we have a link between them. I think? They are clearly related anyway.

Also I think `(Fin.repeat m a)  ∘ Fin.rev = Fin.repeat m (a ∘ Fin.rev)`?

Also, I proved `Fin.rev_last` recently, just haven't PR'd it. I have a somewhat simpler proof in case you want it. I suspect you may also want `Fin.rev_zero`.
```
lemma rev_last {m : ℕ} : (last m).rev = 0 := by
  rw [ext_iff, val_rev, val_last, val_zero, tsub_self]

lemma rev_zero {m : ℕ} : (0 : Fin (m + 1)).rev = (last m) := rfl
```

`(Fin.insertNth i x p) ∘ Fin.rev = Fin.insertNth (Fin.rev i) x (p ∘ Fin.rev)`, I think? Or something like that.

When you start to think about it there really are quite a lot of little lemmas that we ought to have here and it would be good for the scope not to grow too much... but we should ought to do it.

> `(Fin.append a b) ∘ Fin.rev = Fin.append (b ∘ Fin.rev) (a ∘ Fin.rev)`

You need a cast as well (if we want to allow `a` and `b` to be of different length), so it becomes
`(Fin.append a b) ∘ Fin.rev = Fin.append (b ∘ Fin.rev) (a ∘ Fin.rev) ∘ (Fin.cast <| Nat.add_comm ..)`

> `(Fin.insertNth i x p) ∘ Fin.rev = Fin.insertNth (Fin.rev i) x (p ∘ Fin.rev)`, I think? Or something like that.
> 
> When you start to think about it there really are quite a lot of little lemmas that we ought to have here and it would be good for the scope not to grow too much... but we should ought to do it.

We should be careful here. I started this PR because I needed these specific lemmas and figured it'd be easier to review them separately. If the response to that is "you ought to prove all these other theorems as well", that's heavily dis-incentivizing smaller PRs, which I don't think is a good direction.

As a compromise, I'll add the statement (and similar results if you want), but as a `proof_wanted`, is that ok?

Ooh, I've not seen `proof_wanted` before. Yes, that sounds fine. Having been on the other end of this I know how frustrating scope creep can be, and you're right not to let me do it to you. I just always worry about "gaps" - having a way to go "there's a gap here,
someone should go back and fill it" sounds excellent.

I tried to prove `(Fin.append a b) ∘ Fin.rev = Fin.append (b ∘ Fin.rev) (a ∘ Fin.rev)` but found that the `Fin` tuple API has a lot of holes still. I've added a few lemmas, but ultimately decided to stub this result out as a `proof_wanted` as well.

>  Of which both these results are a consequence because we have a link between them. I think?

I'm sure this is true, but the proof strategy for `Fin.append_rev` that I have in mind requires `Fin.cons_rev`, so we need an independent proof of the latter anyway.
I'm going have a look at this (golfing existing proofs and proving the `proof_wanted` statement) later tonight.
All comments have been addressed. Please let us know if anything else should be changed.

:v: alexkeizer can now approve this pull request. To approve and merge a pull request, simply reply with `bors r+`. More detailed instructions are available [here](https://bors.tech/documentation/getting-started/#reviewing-pull-requests).
bors r+

```suggestion
@[simp] lemma rev_last (n : ℕ) : Fin.rev (Fin.last n) = 0 := by
```
You should add `snoc_comp_rev` too, which should follow trivially via some lemma about moving things over equivalences.
done
Can you add the applied versions, `Fin.snoc f a (Fin.rev i) = Fin.cons a (f ∘ Fin.rev) i`, too? Those strike me as useful for rewrites.
Sure, what is the naming convention for that, `snoc_rev`?
How bad do things become if you try to state / prove this for a dependent tuple?

The statement requires some extra `_root_.cast`s. In the non-dependent case these simplify away, allow us to trivially recover the current statement, but it does limit the usefulness in the dependent case.
```lean
theorem cons_rev (a : α 0) (f : (i : Fin n) → α i.succ) (i : Fin <| n + 1) :
    cons a f i.rev
    = snoc (α := α ∘ Fin.rev)
        (fun i => _root_.cast (by simp; congr; exact (sorry : succ (rev i) = rev (castSucc i))) <| f i.rev)
        (_root_.cast (by simp) a) i
```

The most annoying part is that the current proof relies on `Fin.consInduction`, which only works on non-dependent tuples. Generalizing induction to dependent tuples seems out of scope.
This lemma looks like it might be the wrong way round?
Probably, you're right. Feel free to change it.
I wonder what the general property of a function that commutes with succAbove in this way is?
Please prove using `insertNth_rev`
Done.

**[lint-style]** reported by [reviewdog](https://github.com/reviewdog/reviewdog) :dog:
```suggestion (Fin.insertNth i x p) ∘ Fin.rev = Fin.insertNth (Fin.rev i) x (p ∘ Fin.rev) := by ```

I think this is the same as
```suggestion
@[simp] lemma cast_eq_self (a : Fin n) : cast rfl a = a := rfl
```

Non-terminal `simp`s without `only` are not allowed in Mathlib. Please try one of these suggestions:
```suggestion
  apply insertNth_rev
```
```suggestion
  simp [insertNth_rev]
```
or even use `funext <| insertNth_rev ..` as a term-mode proof.
Also, please move this lemma right after `insertNth_rev`. Otherwise LGTM. Thanks!

bors d+
